prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: sigma Orionis Class II Band6
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: 92 sources in sigma Orionis, 2 basebands for continuum and 3 windows in 2 basebands for the 2-1 lines of CO/13CO/C18O

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
The correlator setup provides three high spectral resolution windows centered on the CO, 13CO, and C18O 2-1 lines as these provide the best diagnostics of the gas content in the disks. We use spectral averaging to lower the data rate while still maintaining sufficiently high spectral velocity resolution to resolve the lines and study disk kinematics.
The 13CO and CO lines lie near the edges of their respective baseband. We have verified with technical support via the Helpdesk that such a setup has been tested and is ok. The noise may be a little higher (10-20% depending on source velocity) than the OT prediction but there are no official guidelines for this and it would not affect our science goals at a significant level.
We also have two broad basebands to study the continuum emission. These are separated from each other by almost 18 GHz to improve the imaging fidelity and provide some spectral index information for the brighter sources. The LSB continuum window contains the potentially detectable 3-2 transitions of DCO+ and DCN which can trace the presence of cold gas and CO snowlines (Mathews et al. 2013, A&A, 557, 132), and we therefore use moderate spectral resolution, 1.5 km/s, for this baseband.

This range, 0.24-3.7 arcseconds, corresponds to 100-1500 AU at the 420 pc distance to sigma Orionis and is well matched to the typical sizes of circumstellar disks. We can therefore measure the gas and dust content of the inner, planet-forming regions of the disk without over-resolving them and can constrain sizes and radial gradients for the larger and brighter disks.

The requested RMS is chosen to provide a 3 to 4 sigma detection of the mean continuum flux, as determined from the source stacking of the JCMT SCUBA-2 map and using a spectral index of 2 to 3 to interpolate to the lower ALMA observing frequency. Some sources (particularly the individually detected JCMT objects) will be detected at much higher sensitivity and we can do further analysis, whereas we can provide stringent limits on the planet forming capabilities of those disks that are undetected.
The corresponding line rms is sufficient to detect Jupiter mass levels of gas, as shown by our models in Williams & Best (2014, ApJ, 788, 59; Figure 3 of proposal). We observe at high spectral resolution because we can integrate in velocity without loss of sensitivity while preserving the ability to study disk kinematics for the brighter sources.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: The prevalence of extrasolar Neptunes, with masses that are large enough to undergo runaway growth in the presence of gas suggests that the timescale for planetary core formation and disk gas dissipation must be quite similar. We propose to examine this directly by measuring the gas and dust content of circumstellar disks in the middle-aged (~3-5 Myr old) sigma Orionis cluster. Our sample consists of all 92 spectroscopically identified members of the cluster with Spitzer mid-infrared excesses. Our previous JCMT/SMA observations show that disks have low, but detectable, dust masses and are associated with gas. We will achieve a dust mass sensitivity of two Earth masses, sufficient to detect the mean level of continuum emission. We will also be able to measure the gas content of the disks to Jupiter mass sensitivity through observations of the 13CO and C18O 2-1 lines. This sensitive, uniform study of a large, similarly-aged sample will be a benchmark for disk evolution studies and inform planetary synthesis models. If insufficient gas remains in these middle-aged disks to form Jupiters, we will be able to place firm limits on the formation history of our Solar System.
prp:ObsProposal.prp:scientificCategoryString: Circumstellar disks, exoplanets and the solar system
